First Read: 13-Jan-26
HB160 Enrolled
1 Enrolled, An Act,
2
3 Relating to Tuscaloosa County; to amend Section 1 of
4 Act 80-356 (1980 Regular Session, p. 835) and Section 1 of Act
5 88-317 (1988 Regular Session, p. 481); to further provide for
6 overtime for certain public safety employees.
7 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
8 Section 1. Section 1 of Act 80-356 (1980 Regular
9 Session, p. 835), as last amended by Act 2022-407 (2022
10 Regular Session), is amended to read as follows:
11 "Section 1. (a) Any law enforcement officer in the
12 service of Tuscaloosa County or any city located in the
13 county, or who is employed under a L.E.A.A. or L.E.P.A. grant,
14 and who is assigned to duty for more than eight hours during
15 any one day or for more than 40 hours during any calendar
16 week, shall be paid time and one-half for those excess hours
17 worked, or he or she shall be given time and one-half
18 compensatory leave. It shall be at the sole option of the law
19 enforcement officer affected by this subsection whether he or
20 she shall receive overtime pay or compensatory leave.
21 (b) Notwithstanding subsection (a), upon adoption by
22 resolution of the city council of the City of Northport or the
23 City of Tuscaloosa, Alabama, that city may implement the
24 scheduling of four 10-hour shifts per week rather than five
25 8-hour shifts per week for certain positions in its police
26 department, and any affected law enforcement officer who is
27 assigned to duty for more than 10 hours during any one day or
28 for more than 40 hours during any calendar week shall be paid
Page 1

for more than 40 hours during any calendar week shall be paid
HB160 Enrolled
29 time and one-half for those excess hours worked, or he or she
30 shall be given time and one-half compensation leave. It shall
31 be at the sole option of the law enforcement officer whether
32 he or she shall receive overtime pay or compensatory leave.
33 This subsection shall apply only to those City of Northport or
34 City of Tuscaloosa law enforcement officers who are assigned
35 to four 10-hour shifts per week. All other City of Northport
36 or City of Tuscaloosa law enforcement officers assigned to
37 five 8-hour shifts shall remain under subsection (a).
38 (c) An individual employed as the City of Tuscaloosa's
39 Executive Director of Public Safety shall not be eligible for
40 any overtime pay or compensatory leave provided under this
41 section."
42 Section 2. Section 1 of Act 88-317 (1988 Regular
43 Session, p. 481) is amended to read as follows:
44 "Section 1. (a) Any full-time paid employee engaged in
45 "fire protection activities" in any municipality in Tuscaloosa
46 County shall receive overtime pay at a rate of time and
47 one-half the regular rate of pay or shall be given time and
48 one-half compensatory leave for hours worked in excess of 24
49 hours in a tour of duty or 53 hours in a calendar week.
50 (b)(1) Paid hours worked may be averaged according to
51 the United States Fair Labor Standards Act, as amended, and
52 the work week hours as used in this act shall decline in the
53 future to coincide with all succeeding United States
54 Department of Labor regulations.
55 (2) Such A municipality may institute a shorter work
56 week than the United States Department of Labor requires if
Page 2

week than the United States Department of Labor requires if
HB160 Enrolled
57 they so desire.
58 (c) Gross pay received for a normal work week or work
59 period at the passage of this bill, shall be gross pay or base
60 pay for a 53 hour 53-hour work week, and all succeeding raises
61 shall raise such the gross pay or base pay accordingly.
62 (d) All paid leave of absences shall be counted as
63 hours worked.
64 (e) And, it It shall be the sole option of the employee
65 as to whether he or she shall receive overtime pay or
66 compensatory leave.
67 (f) An individual employed as the City of Tuscaloosa's
68 Executive Director of Public Safety shall not be eligible to
69 any overtime pay or compensatory leave provided under this
70 section."
71 Section 3. This act shall become effective on October
72 1, 2026.
